   <xs:complexType name="section">
      <xs:annotation>
         <xs:documentation>
            <xd:section xmlns:xd="http://www.oecd.org/ns/schema/xdocs">
               <xd:title>Categories</xd:title>
               <xd:p>structural, publishing</xd:p>
            </xd:section> Section structural publishing <xd:section
               xmlns:xd="http://www.oecd.org/ns/schema/xdocs">
               <xd:title>Notes</xd:title>
               <xd:p>Sections are the primary structural component of structured documents. Most of the
                  semantic structures are specialised types of sections. Sections may be nested arbitrarily
                  deeply. Heading levels are then defined purely by section nesting. </xd:p>
            </xd:section>
            <xd:section xmlns:xd="http://www.oecd.org/ns/schema/xdocs">
               <xd:title>Definition</xd:title>
               <xd:p> A section is the basic structural component of all OECD.Author documents. </xd:p>
               <xd:p>The modelling workshop defined a section as a hierarchical component of a document with a
                  title and text that could be considered a child. Sections may contain other sections and all
                  block content. </xd:p>
               <xd:p> In order to avoid ambiguity this model allows block content to occur in a section until
                  the first sub section is created. Following that point, only subsections may be created.
                  This ensures that the document model does not become ambiguous. </xd:p>
               <xd:p> Components and models derived from the basic section will often add additional
                  constraints to this model. Models defined by metadata area unlikely to add constraints
                  whereas publishing models such as chapters and parts will almost always do so.</xd:p>
            </xd:section>
         </xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
      <xs:sequence>
